# V1.17 Welle B — SSH allowed-signers trust root for `git verify-tag`.
#
# Format: `<principal> <key-type> <base64-key>` per line, comments with `#`.
# This is the canonical OpenSSH `allowed_signers` file format consumed by
# `ssh-keygen -Y verify` (which `git verify-tag` invokes when
# `gpg.format = ssh`).
#
# WHO IS LISTED
#   Every entry in this file is a maintainer key authorised to sign
#   `v*` release tags on this repo. Adding a key here grants release-
#   signing authority; removing a key revokes it.
#
# WHY THIS FILE EXISTS (the threat addressed)
#   Without tag-signing enforcement, an attacker with `contents: write`
#   on this repo (e.g. compromised maintainer GitHub PAT, repo-takeover)
#   can push a `v*` tag pointing at a smuggled commit. The
#   `wasm-publish.yml` workflow auto-fires on `push: tags: ['v*']` and
#   would publish the smuggled bytes to npm before any human notices.
#   With this file + the verification step in `wasm-publish.yml`, an
#   unsigned-or-untrusted-key tag push fails the publish gate inside
#   the same workflow run, BEFORE any `npm publish` step.
#
# HOW VERIFICATION WORKS
#   * `wasm-publish.yml` step 1 runs `tools/verify-tag-signatures.sh
#     "$GITHUB_REF_NAME"` (the just-pushed tag), which calls
#     `git verify-tag` with `gpg.ssh.allowedSignersFile` pointed here.
#   * `verify-tag-signatures.yml` (separate workflow) re-verifies all
#     `v*` tags weekly via cron — catches expired keys, revoked keys,
#     or any historical tag that lost its signed status (e.g. force-
#     push attempt).
#
# HOW TO ROTATE
#   Removing a key from this file is the revocation. The next CI run
#   (push, cron, or workflow_dispatch) that re-verifies a tag signed
#   by the removed key will fail. Past releases stay signed by the
#   key as committed at that release tag's snapshot of this file —
#   removing a key now does NOT retroactively invalidate a release;
#   it just refuses to verify the tag against the CURRENT trust root.
#   For a hard revocation that retroactively invalidates a known-bad
#   tag, the operator-side flow is: remove the key, force-push-delete
#   the tag (requires repo-admin + tag-protection-rule override), and
#   re-publish from a new tag signed by a non-compromised key.
#
# HOW TO ADD A KEY
#   `tools/setup-tag-signing.sh add <principal> <ssh-pubkey-path>`
#   appends to this file with consistent formatting. Manual edits
#   are OK as long as the format stays one-entry-per-line and the
#   key-type is one of `ssh-ed25519`, `ssh-rsa` (>= 3072-bit), or
#   `sk-ssh-ed25519@openssh.com` (FIDO2/WebAuthn-backed). DO NOT add
#   `ecdsa-sha2-*` keys without the operator weighing the curve-
#   parameter footgun (NIST P-256/384/521 are fine, but other curves
#   leak info under crafted-message attacks). DO NOT add deprecated
#   key types (`ssh-dss`/DSA).
#
# WHY SSH (not GPG, not Sigstore/gitsign)
#   * SSH keys are already in maintainers' GitHub accounts (`/keys`
#     endpoint), no separate keyserver / OIDC infrastructure needed.
#   * Git 2.34+ has first-class SSH signing support; no plugins.
#   * Works on Windows out-of-the-box (Sigstore/gitsign tooling on
#     Windows is rough; defer to V1.18 as additive enhancement).
#   * Trust root is in-repo (auditable), not pinned to an external
#     OIDC issuer's certificate transparency log.
